Here's an implementation of a queue using two stacks in Python:
```python
class Queue:
    def __init__(self):
        self.in_stack = Stack()
        self.out_stack = Stack()

    def enqueue(self, item):
        self.in_stack.push(item)

    def dequeue(self):
        if not self.out_stack.isEmpty():
            return self.out_stack.pop()

        while not self.in_stack.isEmpty():
            self.out_stack.push(self.in_stack.pop())

        return self.out_stack.pop()


class Stack:
    def __init__(self):
        self.items = []

    def push(self, item):
        self.items.append(item)

    def pop(self):
        if len(self.items) == 0:
            raise ValueError("Stack is empty")

        return self.items.pop()

if __name__ == '__main__':
    q = Queue()
    q.enqueue(1)
    q.enqueue(2)
    q.enqueue(3)

    print(q.dequeue())  # outputs 1
    print(q.dequeue())  # outputs 2
    print(q.dequeue())  # outputs 3


```
This code creates two stacks: one for the input and one for the output. The queue uses the following process to enqueue and dequeue items:
- When an item is added to the queue through enqueue(), it is pushed onto the input stack.
- If the out_stack is not empty, then its topmost element is popped and returned as the result of dequeue(). Otherwise, we start popping elements from the input stack and pushing them onto the output stack until the output stack is no longer empty. Finally, we pop the last element that was pushed onto the output stack and return it as the result of dequeue(). This ensures that the order of items in the queue remains FIFO.

The algorithm you're describing is called "Set Intersection", and it can be implemented as follows:
```cpp
// Function to return set intersection of arr1[low..high] 
//   and arr2[mid..end]. Assumes that low <= mid && high >= end
set<int> intersect(vector<int>& arr1, int low, int high,
                    vector<int>& arr2, int mid, int end) {
  if (low > mid or high < end)
    return set<int>(); // No overlapping intervals

  // Check for intersection between current intervals
  int i = mid, j = low;
  while (i <= end and j <= high) {
    if (arr1[j] == arr2[i])
      return set<int>(arr1[j]);
    else if (arr1[j] < arr2[i])
      ++j;
    else
      ++i;
  }

  return intersect(arr1, low, high, arr2, mid+1, end); // Move on to next interval
}

// Driver code
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

void printArray(vector<int>& arr, string name) {
  cout << name << ": ";
  for (auto x : arr)
    cout << x << " ";
  cout << endl;
}

int main() {
  vector<int> arr1 = {1, 3, 5, 7};
  vector<int> arr2 = {2, 6, 8, 10};

  printArray(arr1, "arr1");
  printArray(arr2, "arr2");

  set<int> ans = intersect(arr1, 0, arr1.size(),
                            arr2, 0, arr2.size());

  cout << "Intersection: ";
  copy(ans.begin(), ans.end(), 
        ostream_iterator<int>(cout, "\n"));

  return 0;
}
```
This implementation uses nested loops to check whether each element in arr1 appears in arr2. If an element matches, we add it to our output set ans. When we encounter an element from arr1 that doesn't match anything in arr2, we move on to the next interval in arr1, effectively skipping over all remaining elements in arr2 that could possibly match. Similarly, when we encounter an element from arr2 that doesn't match anything in arr1, we move on to the next interval in arr2, effectively skipping over all remaining elements in arr1 that could possibly match. This process continues until either array runs out of elements or we successfully identify an intersection. The function also handles the case where arr1 ends before arr2 begins, or vice versa.

Note that this solution has time complexity O(m*n), where m and n are the lengths of arr1 and arr2 respectively. We can improve upon this by sorting both arrays beforehand, bringing the time complexity down to O(mn log mn). Additionally, instead of using a plain old STL set, we could implement a custom binary search tree-based structure which allows us to perform insertions and lookups in constant time, further reducing the overall runtime to O(mn). But those optimizations go beyond the scope of your original question.
